= IF THEN ELSE ("Data GMH Start Rate (mean) - filtered"=0,0,IF THEN ELSE ("Data GMH New Patient Wait Time (median)"<Min Transfer Time to GMH,Min Transfer Time to GMH,"Data GMH New Patient Wait Time (median)"))
Description: It is possible for the estimate for the median wait time to be zero, if the team sees many walk-in patients. However the model needs the wait time to represent the average, thus a value of zero is not feasible. In these rare cases, we prevent the model from using a zero average wait time, instead using the Minimum Transfer Time. If the relevant engagement duration is zero (indicating no patients follow this pathway), then the wait time is also set to zero.

F,A

(1/wk)
= (White Noise - Pink Noise)/"Noise Correlation Time = jaggedness"
Description: Change in the pink noise value; Pink noise is a first order exponential smoothing delay of the whitenoise input.
Present in 1 view:
  • Model
Used by:
  • Pink Noise - Pink Noise is first-order autocorrelated noise. Pink noise provides a realistic noise input tomodels in which the next random shock depends in part on the previous shocks. The usercan specify the correlation time. The mean is 0 and the standard deviation is specifiedby the user.

A
(Episode)
= GET DIRECT CONSTANTS('ModelParameters.xlsx', 'SPParams','D26')
Description: The number of care episodes used to calculate the related rate-governing parameter.
Present in 1 view:
  • Model
Used by:
  • Flag GMH Engagement Time before Ending EpC - The flag is "on" (shows a zero) when a model parameter is estimated from too small a number of care episodes to be trusted (based on the team's Threshold for Inclusion).
  • Sum EpC no HRF - The sum of all episode counts related to flows of patients without a High Risk Flag; used as the denominator in the decision for whether any model parameter related to the flow of patient without a HRF should be "trusted" and thus included in the simulation.
Default sp i v4 2020 12 17
(Default)		 #35
A
(Episode)
= GET DIRECT CONSTANTS('ModelParameters.xlsx', 'SPParams','D5')
Description: The number of care episodes used to calculate the related rate-governing parameter.
Present in 1 view:
  • Model
Used by:
  • Flag GMH High Risk Flag Rate EpC - The flag is "on" (shows a zero) when a model parameter is estimated from too small a number of care episodes to be trusted (based on the team's Threshold for Inclusion). Evaluating model parameters relating to HRFs is based only on the sum of episodes for parameters relating to HRFs, not all episodes in the team's patient cohort.
  • Sum EpC w High Risk Flag - The sum of all episode counts related to flows of patients with a High Risk Flag; used as the denominator in the decision for whether any model parameter related to the flow of patient with a HRF should be "trusted" and thus included in the simulation.

Present in 1 view:
  • Model
Used by:
  • "Adjusted Data GMH New Patient Wait Time (median)" - It is possible for the estimate for the median wait time to be zero, if the team sees many walk-in patients. However the model needs the wait time to represent the average, thus a value of zero is not feasible. In these rare cases, we prevent the model from using a zero average wait time, instead using the Minimum Transfer Time. If the relevant engagement duration is zero (indicating no patients follow this pathway), then the wait time is also set to zero.

  • "Adjusted Data PC/PCMHI to GMH Wait Time (median)" - It is possible for the estimate for the median wait time to be zero, if the team sees many walk-in patients. However the model needs the wait time to represent the average, thus a value of zero is not feasible. In these rare cases, we prevent the model from using a zero average wait time, instead using the Minimum Transfer Time. If the relevant engagement duration is zero (indicating no patients follow this pathway), then the wait time is also set to zero.

= ∫EQ HR Flag Rate in SMH-EQ HR Flag Transfer from SMH to GMH-EQ HR Unflag Rate in SMH-EQ SMH HFR Pts to Res Rate dt + [Initial SMH High Risk Flag Patients]
Present in 1 view:
  • Model
Used by:
  • EQ HR Flag Transfer from SMH to GMH - Patients at high risk for suicide are moved from SMH to GMH. This is determined by the number of patients in SMH with a high risk flag and median amount of time these patients remain in SMH before transfer to GMH. This time parameter is estimated from team data, if the team deems the cohort size large enough to be trustworthy, otherwise zero.
  • EQ HR Unflag Rate in SMH - Patients with high symptoms deemed no longer at high risk for suicide. This is determined by the number of patients at high risk and median amount of time these patients retain a high risk flag. This time parameter is estimated from team data, if the team deems the cohort size large enough to be trustworthy, otherwise zero.
  • EQ Initial SMH Manageable Total Patients
  • EQ SMH HFR Pts to Res Rate - Patients at high risk for suicide are moved from SMH to residential treatment. This is determined by the number of patients in SMH with a high risk flag and median amount of time these patients remain in SMH before transfer to residential treatment. This time parameter is estimated from team data, if the team deems the cohort size large enough to be trustworthy, otherwise zero.
Default sp i v4 2020 12 17

  • EQ SMH Pts to Res Rate

Description: As workload increases, the quality of care provided by a team decreases, and vice versa. This effect is limited to 2x, as even the lowest workload could no more than double the original quality of care (i.e., no more than halve the current Time to Improve and the Time to Unflag). There is no limit to the detrimental effect increasing workload has on care quality, and could (potentially) drive "Time to Improve" and "Time to UnFlag" toward infinity.

  • GMH Effect of Patient Load on Ability to Detect Symptom Changes - As workload increases, the ability of providers to detect symptom changes decreases, and vice versa. This effect directly impacts the variable "Time to Detect." This effect is limited to 3x, as the highest load could not do more than triple the original Time to Detect. There is no limit to the positive effect decreasing workload has on providers' ability to detect symptom changes. (pct)
  • GMH Effect of Patient Load on Care Quality - As workload increases, the quality of care provided by a team decreases, and vice versa. This effect is limited to 2x, as even the lowest workload could no more than double the original quality of care (i.e., no more than halve the current Time to Improve and the Time to Unflag). There is no limit to the detrimental effect increasing workload has on care quality, and could (potentially) drive "Time to Improve" and "Time to UnFlag" toward infinity.
  • GMH Effect of Patient Load on Manageable Total Patients - If workload experiences a sustained increase, eventually the total patients the setting can manage decreases, due to provider fatigue and burnout. This effect seeks to represent both small changes (providers taking more sick days) and large changes (providers quitting entirely) in supply. The effect can only go below 1, as below-average workload cannot increase supply. (pct)
  • GMH Patient Load Affects New Care Episode Start Rate - As workload increases, the ability of providers to start new patients decreases, and vice versa. This effect directly impacts the "Patient Start Rate." This effect seeks to represent the physical reality of having a schedule that is too full to start new patients. There is no limit to the detrimental effect increasing workload has on start rate -- a high-enough workload could cut patient starts to zero. (pct)
Default sp i v4 2020 12 17
(Default)		 #293
A
(Dmnl)
= IF THEN ELSE(Time>0,SMOOTHI(GMH Patient Load^-User GMH Sensitivity of Start Rate to Patient Load,Time for Load to Affect Start Rate,1),1)
Description: As workload increases, the ability of providers to start new patients decreases, and vice versa. This effect directly impacts the "Patient Start Rate." This effect seeks to represent the physical reality of having a schedule that is too full to start new patients. There is no limit to the detrimental effect increasing workload has on start rate -- a high-enough workload could cut patient starts to zero. (pct)
Present in 1 view:
  • Model
Used by:
  • GMH Effect of Patient Load on Start Rate 0 - not sensitive close to neutral value (1), to prevent Vensim calc errors from creating feedback.

  • "Adjusted Data GMH New Patient Wait Time (median)" - It is possible for the estimate for the median wait time to be zero, if the team sees many walk-in patients. However the model needs the wait time to represent the average, thus a value of zero is not feasible. In these rare cases, we prevent the model from using a zero average wait time, instead using the Minimum Transfer Time. If the relevant engagement duration is zero (indicating no patients follow this pathway), then the wait time is also set to zero.

(Default)		 #457
A
(Dmnl)
= IF THEN ELSE("PC/PCMHI Total Patients"=0,1,XIDZ("PC/PCMHI Total Patients","PC/PCMHI Manageable Total Patients",1))
Description: The number of patients recommended to start in this setting each week, who are not transferring in from another setting (i.e., they are either enitrely new to mental health care, or are seeking to start concurrent treatment while remaining in a different setting). (pct)
Present in 1 view:
  • Model
Used by:
  • "PC/PCMHI Effect of Patient Load on Ability to Detect Symptom Changes" - As workload increases, the quality of care provided by a team decreases, and vice versa. This effect is limited to 2x, as even the lowest workload could no more than double the original quality of care (i.e., no more than halve the current Time to Improve and the Time to Unflag). There is no limit to the detrimental effect increasing workload has on care quality, and could (potentially) drive "Time to Improve" and "Time to UnFlag" toward infinity. (pct)
  • "PC/PCMHI Effect of Patient Load on Care Quality" - If workload experiences a sustained increase, eventually the total patients the setting can manage decreases, due to provider fatigue and burnout. This effect seeks to represent both small changes (providers taking more sick days) and large changes (providers quitting entirely) in supply. The effect can only go below 1, as below-average workload cannot increase supply. (pct)
  • "PC/PCMHI Effect of Patient Load on Manageable Total Patients" - As workload increases, the ability of providers to start new patients decreases, and vice versa. This effect directly impacts the "Patient Start Rate." This effect seeks to represent the physical reality of having a schedule that is too full to start new patients. There is no limit to the detrimental effect increasing workload has on start rate -- a high-enough workload could cut patient starts to zero. (pct)
  • "PC/PCMHI Patient Load Affects New Care Episode Start Rate" - As wait times to step up to GMH increase (both for PC/PCMHI patients who transfer and those who start in GMH without leaving PC/PCMHI), PC/PCMHI providers will be less willing to recommend that their patients step down. There is no limit to the detrimental effect GMH wait times have on PC/PCMHI step up recommendations; however, this effect is limited to a maximum of 1.5x, as very low wait times could increase step up recommendations by no more than 50% over the original rate. (pct)
Default sp i v4 2020 12 17
(Default)		 #458
A
(Dmnl)
= IF THEN ELSE(Time>0,SMOOTHI("PC/PCMHI Patient Load"^-"User PC/PCMHI Sensitivity of Start Rate to Patient Load",Time for Load to Affect Start Rate,1), 1)
Description: As wait times to step up to GMH increase (both for PC/PCMHI patients who transfer and those who start in GMH without leaving PC/PCMHI), PC/PCMHI providers will be less willing to recommend that their patients step down. There is no limit to the detrimental effect GMH wait times have on PC/PCMHI step up recommendations; however, this effect is limited to a maximum of 1.5x, as very low wait times could increase step up recommendations by no more than 50% over the original rate. (pct)
Present in 1 view:
  • Model
Used by:
  • "PC/PCMHI Effect of Patient Load on Start Rate 0" - not sensitive close to neutral value (1), to prevent Vensim calc errors from creating feedback.

(Default)		 #569
A
(Dmnl)
= IF THEN ELSE(SMH Total Patients=0,1,XIDZ(SMH Total Patients, SMH Manageable Total Patients,1))
Description: The number of patients recommended to start in this setting each week, who are not transferring in from another setting (i.e., they are either enitrely new to mental health care, or are seeking to start concurrent treatment while remaining in a different setting). (pct)
Present in 1 view:
  • Model
Used by:
  • SMH Effect of Patient Load on Ability to Detect Symptom Changes - As wait times to step down to GMH increase (both for SMH patients who transfer and those who start in GMH without leaving SMH), SMH providers will be less willing to recommend that their patients step down. There is no limit to the detrimental effect GMH wait times have on SMH step down recommendations; however, this effect is limited to a maximum of 1.5x, as very low wait times could increase step down recommendations by no more than 50% over the original rate. (pct)
  • SMH Effect of Patient Load on Care Quality - As workload increases, the ability of providers to detect symptom changes decreases, and vice versa. This effect directly impacts the variable "Time to Detect." This effect is limited to 3x, as the highest load could not do more than triple the original Time to Detect. There is no limit to the positive effect decreasing workload has on providers' ability to detect symptom changes. (pct)
  • SMH Effect of Patient Load on Manageable Total Patients - As workload increases, the quality of care provided by a team decreases, and vice versa. This effect is limited to 2x, as even the lowest workload could no more than double the original quality of care (i.e., no more than halve the current Time to Improve and the Time to Unflag). There is no limit to the detrimental effect increasing workload has on care quality, and could (potentially) drive "Time to Improve" and "Time to UnFlag" toward infinity. (pct)
  • SMH Patient Load Affects New Care Episode Start Rate - If workload experiences a sustained increase, eventually the total patients the setting can manage decreases, due to provider fatigue and burnout. This effect seeks to represent both small changes (providers taking more sick days) and large changes (providers quitting entirely) in supply. The effect can only go below 1, as below-average workload cannot increase supply. (pct)
Default sp i v4 2020 12 17
(Default)		 #570
A
(Dmnl)

The effect can only go below 1, as below-average workload cannot increase supply. (pct)

Present in 1 view:
  • Model
Used by:
  • GMH Patient Load Affects New Care Episode Start Rate - As workload increases, the ability of providers to start new patients decreases, and vice versa. This effect directly impacts the "Patient Start Rate." This effect seeks to represent the physical reality of having a schedule that is too full to start new patients. There is no limit to the detrimental effect increasing workload has on start rate -- a high-enough workload could cut patient starts to zero. (pct)
  • "PC/PCMHI Patient Load Affects New Care Episode Start Rate" - As wait times to step up to GMH increase (both for PC/PCMHI patients who transfer and those who start in GMH without leaving PC/PCMHI), PC/PCMHI providers will be less willing to recommend that their patients step down. There is no limit to the detrimental effect GMH wait times have on PC/PCMHI step up recommendations; however, this effect is limited to a maximum of 1.5x, as very low wait times could increase step up recommendations by no more than 50% over the original rate. (pct)
  • SMH Patient Load Affects New Care Episode Start Rate - If workload experiences a sustained increase, eventually the total patients the setting can manage decreases, due to provider fatigue and burnout. This effect seeks to represent both small changes (providers taking more sick days) and large changes (providers quitting entirely) in supply. The effect can only go below 1, as below-average workload cannot increase supply. (pct)

This effect is limited to 2x, as even the lowest workload could no more than double the original quality of care (i.e., no more than halve the current Time to Improve and the Time to Unflag). There is no limit to the detrimental effect increasing workload has on care quality, and could (potentially) drive "Time to Improve" and "Time to UnFlag" toward infinity.
Default sp i v4 2020 12 17
(Default)		 #664
G
(Dmnl [0,2,0.1])
= GAME (1)
Description: Initially set to "1," where if the patient load doubles, then the time to detect is doubled. Lowering the sensitivity to "0.5" will reduce the effect (if load doubles, then time to detect only increases by 40%), and increasing the sensitivity to "2" will increase the effect (if load doubles, then time to detect increases by 300%). (pct)
Present in 1 view:
  • Model
Used by:
  • GMH Effect of Patient Load on Ability to Detect Symptom Changes - As workload increases, the ability of providers to detect symptom changes decreases, and vice versa. This effect directly impacts the variable "Time to Detect." This effect is limited to 3x, as the highest load could not do more than triple the original Time to Detect. There is no limit to the positive effect decreasing workload has on providers' ability to detect symptom changes. (pct)

The effect can only go below 1, as below-average workload cannot increase supply. (pct)

(Dmnl [0,2,0.1])
= GAME (1)
Description: Initially set to "1," where if the patient load doubles, then quality is halved. Lowering the sensitivity to "0.5" will reduce the effect (if load doubles, then quality is only reduced by 30%), and increasing the sensitivity to "2" will increase the effect (if load doubles, then quality is reduced by 75%). (pct)
Present in 1 view:
  • Model
Used by:
  • SMH Effect of Patient Load on Care Quality - As workload increases, the ability of providers to detect symptom changes decreases, and vice versa. This effect directly impacts the variable "Time to Detect." This effect is limited to 3x, as the highest load could not do more than triple the original Time to Detect. There is no limit to the positive effect decreasing workload has on providers' ability to detect symptom changes. (pct)

Description: Initially set to "1," where if the patient load doubles, then the time to detect is doubled. Lowering the sensitivity to "0.5" will reduce the effect (if load doubles, then time to detect only increases by 40%), and increasing the sensitivity to "2" will increase the effect (if load doubles, then time to detect increases by 300%). (pct)
Present in 1 view:
  • Model
Used by:
  • SMH Effect of Patient Load on Ability to Detect Symptom Changes - As wait times to step down to GMH increase (both for SMH patients who transfer and those who start in GMH without leaving SMH), SMH providers will be less willing to recommend that their patients step down. There is no limit to the detrimental effect GMH wait times have on SMH step down recommendations; however, this effect is limited to a maximum of 1.5x, as very low wait times could increase step down recommendations by no more than 50% over the original rate. (pct)

Description: Initially set to "1," where if the patient load doubles, then eventually, total manageable patients is halved. There is no limit to the detrimental effect increasing workload has on care quality, and could (potentially) drive "Time to Improve" and "Time to UnFlag" toward infinity. (pct)

Level Structure †

EQ GMH Early in Care Patients = ∫EQ Transfer into GMH from PC Rate+EQ Transfer into GMH from SMH Rate+EQ Transfer to GMH Rate-EQ Detect High Sympt Pts in GMH Rate-EQ Detect Low Sympt Pt in GMH Rate dt + [Initial GMH Early in Care Patients]
Initial GMH Early in Care Patients = GMH Inflow Check*Usual Initial Patients
    EQ Detect High Sympt Pts in GMH Rate = (ZIDZ(EQ GMH Early in Care Patients , Initial GMH Time to Detect))*(1-"Initial Low Symptom % in GMH")
    EQ Detect Low Sympt Pt in GMH Rate = (ZIDZ(EQ GMH Early in Care Patients,Initial GMH Time to Detect))*"Initial Low Symptom % in GMH"
    EQ Transfer into GMH from PC Rate = EQ Refer to GMH from PCMHI Rate
    EQ Transfer into GMH from SMH Rate = EQ Refer to GMH from SMH Rate
    EQ Transfer to GMH Rate = "Data GMH Start Rate (mean) - filtered"

EQ GMH High Risk Flag Patients = ∫EQ HR Flag Rate in GMH+EQ HR Flag Transfer from PCMHI to GMH+EQ HR Flag Transfer from SMH to GMH-EQ GMH HRF Pts to Res Rate-EQ HR Unflag Rate in GMH dt + [Initial GMH High Risk Flag Patients]
Initial GMH High Risk Flag Patients = GMH HRF Inflow Check*Usual Initial Patients
    EQ GMH HRF Pts to Res Rate = ZIDZ(EQ GMH High Risk Flag Patients , "Data GMH to Residential Time From Flag to Step up - filtered")
    EQ HR Flag Rate in GMH = EQ GMH High Symptom Patients*"EQ Initial GMH High Risk Patient Flag Rate %"
    EQ HR Flag Transfer from PCMHI to GMH = ZIDZ("EQ PC/PCMHI High Risk Flag Patients" , "Data PC/PCMHI to GMH Time from Flag to Step up - filtered")
    EQ HR Flag Transfer from SMH to GMH = ZIDZ(EQ SMH High Risk Flag Patients , "Data SMH to GMH Time from Flag to Step down - filtered")
    EQ HR Unflag Rate in GMH = ZIDZ(EQ GMH High Risk Flag Patients , "Data GMH Time to UnFlag - filtered")

EQ GMH High Symptom Patients = ∫EQ Detect High Sympt Pts in GMH Rate+EQ HR Unflag Rate in GMH-EQ GMH Pts to Res Rate-EQ HR Flag Rate in GMH-EQ Improvement in GMH Rate-EQ Refer to SMH from GMH Rate dt + [Initial GMH High Symptom Patients]
Initial GMH High Symptom Patients = Initial GMH Early in Care Patients+Initial GMH High Risk Flag Patients
    EQ GMH Pts to Res Rate = ZIDZ(EQ GMH High Symptom Patients , "Adjusted GMH to Residential Engagement Time before Step up (median)")
    EQ Improvement in GMH Rate = ZIDZ(EQ GMH High Symptom Patients , Initial GMH Time to Improve w Floor)
    EQ Refer to SMH from GMH Rate = ZIDZ(EQ GMH High Symptom Patients , "Adjusted GMH to SMH Engagement Time Before Step up (median)")

EQ GMH Low Symptom Patients = ∫EQ Improvement in GMH Rate+EQ Detect Low Sympt Pt in GMH Rate-EQ Leave GMH Rate-EQ Refer to PCMHI from GMH Rate dt + [Initial GMH Low Symptom Patients]
Initial GMH Low Symptom Patients = Initial GMH Early in Care Patients+Initial GMH High Risk Flag Patients
    EQ Leave GMH Rate = ZIDZ(EQ GMH Low Symptom Patients , "Adjusted GMH Engagement Time Before Ending (median)")
    EQ Refer to PCMHI from GMH Rate = ZIDZ(EQ GMH Low Symptom Patients , "Adjusted GMH to PC/PCMHI Engagement Time Before Step down (median)")

"EQ PC/PCMHI Early in Care Patients" = ∫EQ Refer to PCMHI from GMH Rate+EQ Transfer into PCMHI from SMH Rate+EQ Transfer into PCMHI Rate-EQ Detect Low Sympt Pt in PCMHI Rate-EQ Detect High Sympt Pts in PCMHI Rate dt + ["Initial PC/PCMHI Early in Care Patients"]
"Initial PC/PCMHI Early in Care Patients" = "PC/PCMHI Inflow Check"*Usual Initial Patients
    EQ Detect High Sympt Pts in PCMHI Rate = (ZIDZ("EQ PC/PCMHI Early in Care Patients" , "Initial PC/PCMHI Time to Detect"))*(1-"Initial PC/PCMHI Low Symptom %")
    EQ Detect Low Sympt Pt in PCMHI Rate = (ZIDZ("EQ PC/PCMHI Early in Care Patients" , "Initial PC/PCMHI Time to Detect"))*"Initial PC/PCMHI Low Symptom %"
    EQ Transfer into PCMHI from SMH Rate = EQ Refer to PCMHI from SMH Rate
    EQ Transfer into PCMHI Rate = "Data PC/PCMHI Start Rate - filtered"

"EQ PC/PCMHI High Risk Flag Patients" = ∫EQ HR Flag Rate in PCMHI-EQ HR Flag Transfer from PCMHI to GMH-EQ HR Unflag Rate in PCMHI-EQ PCMHI HRF Pts to Res Rate dt + ["Initial PC/PCMHI High Risk Flag Patients"]
"Initial PC/PCMHI High Risk Flag Patients" = IF THEN ELSE ("Data PC/PCMHI High Risk Flag Rate - filtered"=0,0,10)
    EQ HR Flag Rate in PCMHI = "EQ PC/PCMHI High Symptom Patients"*"EQ Initial PC/PCMHI High Risk Patient Flag Rate %"
    EQ HR Unflag Rate in PCMHI = ZIDZ("EQ PC/PCMHI High Risk Flag Patients" , "Data PC/PCMHI Time to UnFlag - filtered")
    EQ PCMHI HRF Pts to Res Rate = ZIDZ("EQ PC/PCMHI High Risk Flag Patients","Data PC/PCMHI to Residential Time From Flag to Step up - filtered")

"EQ PC/PCMHI High Symptom Patients" = ∫EQ Detect High Sympt Pts in PCMHI Rate+EQ HR Unflag Rate in PCMHI-EQ HR Flag Rate in PCMHI-EQ Improvement in PCMHI Rate-EQ PCMHI Pts to Res Rate-EQ Refer to GMH from PCMHI Rate-EQ Refer to SMH from PCMHI Rate dt + ["Initial PC/PCMHI High Symptom Patients"]
"Initial PC/PCMHI High Symptom Patients" = "Initial PC/PCMHI Early in Care Patients"
    EQ Improvement in PCMHI Rate = ZIDZ("EQ PC/PCMHI High Symptom Patients" , "Initial PC/PCMHI Time to Improve w Floor")
    EQ PCMHI Pts to Res Rate = ZIDZ("EQ PC/PCMHI High Symptom Patients" , "Adjusted PC/PCMHI to Residential Engagement Time before Step up (median)")
    EQ Refer to GMH from PCMHI Rate = ZIDZ("EQ PC/PCMHI High Symptom Patients" , "Adjusted PC/PCMHI to GMH Engagement Time Before Step up (median)")
    EQ Refer to SMH from PCMHI Rate = ZIDZ("EQ PC/PCMHI High Symptom Patients" , "Adjusted PC/PCMHI to SMH Engagement Time Before Step up (median)")

"EQ PC/PCMHI Low Symptom Patients" = ∫EQ Improvement in PCMHI Rate+EQ Detect Low Sympt Pt in PCMHI Rate-EQ Leave PCMHI Rate dt + ["Initial PC/PCMHI Low Symptom Patients"]
"Initial PC/PCMHI Low Symptom Patients" = "Initial PC/PCMHI Early in Care Patients"
    EQ Leave PCMHI Rate = ZIDZ("EQ PC/PCMHI Low Symptom Patients" , "Adjusted PC/PCMHI Engagement Time Before Ending (median)")

EQ SMH Early in Care Patients = ∫EQ Transfer into SMH from PCMHI Rate+EQ Refer to SMH from GMH Rate+EQ Transfer into SMH Rate-EQ Detect Low Sympt Pt in SMH Rate-EQ Detect High Sympt Pts in SMH Rate dt + [Initial SMH Early in Care Patients]
Initial SMH Early in Care Patients = SMH Inflow Check*Usual Initial Patients
    EQ Detect High Sympt Pts in SMH Rate = (ZIDZ(EQ SMH Early in Care Patients , Initial SMH Time to Detect))*(1-"Initial Low Symptom % in SMH")
    EQ Detect Low Sympt Pt in SMH Rate = (ZIDZ(EQ SMH Early in Care Patients , Initial SMH Time to Detect))*"Initial Low Symptom % in SMH"
    EQ Transfer into SMH from PCMHI Rate = EQ Refer to SMH from PCMHI Rate
    EQ Transfer into SMH Rate = "Data SMH Start Rate (mean) - filtered"

EQ SMH High Risk Flag Patients = ∫EQ HR Flag Rate in SMH-EQ HR Flag Transfer from SMH to GMH-EQ HR Unflag Rate in SMH-EQ SMH HFR Pts to Res Rate dt + [Initial SMH High Risk Flag Patients]
Initial SMH High Risk Flag Patients = IF THEN ELSE ("Data SMH High Risk Flag Rate - filtered"=0,0,10)
    EQ HR Flag Rate in SMH = EQ SMH High Symptpm Patients*"EQ Initial SMH High Risk Patient Flag Rate %"
    EQ HR Unflag Rate in SMH = ZIDZ(EQ SMH High Risk Flag Patients , "Data SMH Time to UnFlag - filtered")
    EQ SMH HFR Pts to Res Rate = ZIDZ(EQ SMH High Risk Flag Patients , "Data SMH to Residential Time From Flag to Step up - filtered")

EQ SMH High Symptpm Patients = ∫EQ HR Unflag Rate in SMH+EQ Detect High Sympt Pts in SMH Rate-EQ HR Flag Rate in SMH-EQ Improvement in SMH Rate-EQ SMH Pts to Res Rate dt + [Initial SMH High Symptom Patients]
Initial SMH High Symptom Patients = Initial SMH Early in Care Patients
    EQ Improvement in SMH Rate = ZIDZ(EQ SMH High Symptpm Patients , Initial SMH Time to Improve w Floor)
    EQ SMH Pts to Res Rate = ZIDZ(EQ SMH High Symptpm Patients , "Adjusted SMH to Residential Engagement Time before Step up (median)")

EQ SMH Low Symptom Patients = ∫EQ Improvement in SMH Rate+EQ Detect Low Sympt Pt in SMH Rate-EQ Leave SMH Rate-EQ Refer to GMH from SMH Rate-EQ Refer to PCMHI from SMH Rate dt + [Initial SMH Low Symptom Patients]
Initial SMH Low Symptom Patients = Initial SMH Early in Care Patients
    EQ Leave SMH Rate = ZIDZ(EQ SMH Low Symptom Patients , "Adjusted SMH Engagement Time Before Ending (median)")
    EQ Refer to GMH from SMH Rate = ZIDZ(EQ SMH Low Symptom Patients , "Adjusted SMH to GMH Engagement Time Before Step down (median)")

GMH Low Symptom Patients = ∫GMH Improvement Rate+GMH Low Symptom Patient Detection Rate-GMH Ending Rate-GMH Low Symptom Patients Community Care Rate-"GMH to PC/PCMHI Recommend Step down Rate" dt + [Initial GMH Low Symptom Patients]
